The work is not done — the implementation does not reject `../` traversal, so the attack the test exercises would still succeed.

The handler only guards against absolute paths:

```js
if (path.isAbsolute(userPath)) throw new Error('forbidden');
return fs.readFileSync(path.join(base, userPath), 'utf8');
```

A payload like `../../etc/passwd` is a *relative* path, so `path.isAbsolute` returns false and nothing is thrown. `path.join(base, '../../etc/passwd')` then collapses the `..` segments and resolves to a location outside `base`, and `fs.readFileSync` reads it. That is exactly the traversal the task asked us to block — the check stops the wrong class of input. The inline comment in the file even concedes this (`insufficient: blocks absolute, not ../`), so the guard is acknowledged-incomplete rather than a subtle miss.

Reading the code against the requirement, the `../` test should fail: it expects a thrown error (or refusal), and this code returns file contents instead.

What it needs is a containment check on the *resolved* path, not an `isAbsolute` check on the raw input. Resolve the join and confirm it stays under the base directory, for example:

```js
const resolved = path.resolve(base, userPath);
const root = path.resolve(base);
if (resolved !== root && !resolved.startsWith(root + path.sep)) {
  throw new Error('forbidden');
}
return fs.readFileSync(resolved, 'utf8');
```

This rejects `../` escapes and absolute paths alike, because both end up resolving outside `root`.

I based this entirely on reading the file as instructed — I did not run the handler or the test, so the failure above is my static reading of the control flow, not an observed test result. If you want, I can apply the containment fix and then actually run the test to confirm.

